Lancashire, East Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire, Lunt in Merseyside, and Lound in Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, and Suffolk, and the surname may derive from any of these. As a Swedish surname it is probably most often ornamental.","German: habitational name from any of the places called Lund or Lunden in Schleswig-Holstein."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Alexander Lound was born in 1375, in Lound, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Gerard de Lounde and Mary Mussell. He married Margaret of Romania in 1395, in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1431, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1375–1431":"1375–1431","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1400–1454":"1400–1454","1410–1460":"1410–1460","–Male":"Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1454":"1454","1431":"1431","1354":"1354","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","York,Yorkshire,England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Boston, Lincolnshire,, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lound, Nottinghamshire, England":"Lound, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":